<br>
The problem here isn't the foreigners.  The problem is that your system is designed to encourage laziness (or more accurately it's designed not to encourage work ethic).  You can't blame people for playing the system to get the most out of it.  If the government creates a program by which I'm eligible for money, you can be damned sure I'm going to sign up for it, and I bet you would too.<br>
<br>
You have created the problem by the system you've chosen.  The way to fix it is to have a system where people have to work to eat (don't bother to argue that some people are disabled etc, I'm not talking about them, I'm talking about those that can work).  You'd be amazed how much more willing to work people are when the government isn't there to give them money if they choose not to work.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=buchalter>Buchalter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New User</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/2/03 12:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2103.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mywebpages.comcast.net/wbbuch1/EQ/tkicons.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Fair Comparison...?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>... comparing the Everquest society with a country's society is a bit of a flawed comparison. In Everquest we all start out equal and you have almost full influence over the success of your character. In real life external situations can influence your ability to gain an income (woops, got a degree in IT and get fired by the boss?). In real life people often are at a disadvantage because of the situation you were born in.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Perhaps all &quot;characters&quot; start out equal, but all players are definitely not.<br>
<br>
As a married father of two, I can tell you I don't have near the amount of time to commit to the game as someone without the same responsibilities.  Most End-Game guilds require six hours of raiding at least four nights a week, and marathon sessions on weekends.  I'd be in divorce court within a month if I ignored my wife and family to that extent.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying there is a perfect correlation between Real World Capitalism and the Everquest Economy.  But I think the principle Maige is trying to illustrate is valid.  Those who have the means/desire to devote more time and energy to EQ reap more rewards than those who do not.<br>
<br>
I think it was Bigem who last suggested that we &quot;disperse the wealth&quot; to the masses and do our best to see that every Man, Woman, and Child in EQ got their fair share and opportunity to enjoy the benefits of the Elemental Planes and a shot at the Plane of Time... we all know how well his ideas were received!  Basically he was told to F-Off and die - If he wanted that priviledge he had to work for it.  Hmmm sounds a lot like Capitalism to me...<br>
<br>
