<br>
That statementis far from the truth. By that logic, 80 % of the people here would be voting right-wing parties. <br>
<br>
People's opinions regarding this is mostly what they are used to. America's system works for America (even though I can list lots of disadvantages) and the Dutch system is working for us (even though you can list lots of disadvantages). I am sure that if I were to be born rich in the USA, my views would've been totally different. But I was born here, relatively poor (for Dutch standards, real poor people don't exist here). I'm not denying that my political views are influenced by the country I was born in. Both systems work, period. It's not like the Netherlands are weak economically.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The problem here isn't the foreigners. The problem is that your system is designed to encourage laziness (or more accurately it's designed not to encourage work ethic). You can't blame people for playing the system to get the most out of it. If the government creates a program by which I'm eligible for money, you can be damned sure I'm going to sign up for it, and I bet you would too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wrong, you are not well-informed about this matter. Foreigners that come here for economic reasons come here to work. By there standards, a few years of work here would make them a wealthy person in their own country. However, the problem is that it is very hard for a foreigner to get a job here. Not only have they the very fact that they're foreigners against them, but most of the time their education isn't high by Dutch standards. The problem here is that these people were admitted in the country. <br>
<br>
Would you stop working for $500-600 / month Ammelen ? Most people want to do something worthwhile with their life, sitting at home collecting wellfare isn't exactly fullfilling. You make it seem like everybody who can abuse the system IS abusing the system. Believe me, that is far from the truth. The largest problem with the system is that people who don't need wellfare somehow cheat the government so that they do get it, not that people who are perfectly capable of landing a job choose not to.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The way to fix it is to have a system where people have to work to eat<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Currently, there just are not enough jobs. Wellfare or not, most of these people would be without a job. Socialistic countries usually have about 2 - 5 % higher unemployment rates than capitalist countries.  This is a sympton (and a negative aspect) of socialism, but in no way is this indicative that the system is disfunctional so there's nothing to fix, thank you very much.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm not saying there is a perfect correlation between Real World Capitalism and the Everquest Economy. But I think the principle Maige is trying to illustrate is valid. Those who have the means/desire to devote more time and energy to EQ reap more rewards than those who do not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For explaining the principle it was a good example, but the principle of capitalism did not need explaining here. It's a poor example to prove a point. Just because most people prefer a capitalistic system in EQ (I am among them), doesn't mean it is the 'best' system for real life countries (note : I'm also not saying that socialism is the best). I think a dictatorship is the best system to lead a guild in EQ, but I would be very opposed to having a dictator rule my country. Drawing analogies is almost always a poor way to proof a point. <p>---------------<br>
